VXLAN Greenfield Import:
========================
1. Greenfield means starting fresh without any existing configs,
   so with no old configs or legacy settings.

2. Import here means bringing in new, ready-made configurations for
   your network devices.

What was there before Greenfield Import:
  > Only basic settings: device name, management IP, and interfaces turned on.
  > No advanced features like BGP, OSPF, VXLAN, or EVPN.
  > No special VLANs, trunks, or high MTU (packet size) settings.
  > No loopback interfaces (used for routing).
  > No overlay or underlay network setups.

  (Vxlan is mainly used for extending layer 2 networks over layer 3 networks,
   so without Vxlan and EVPN, the network is just a simple layer 2 or layer 3 setup.)
  (it solves the problem of limited VLANs by allowing many virtual networks over a physical network)
  (vlan range is 1-4094, vxlan can support up to 16 million segments)

  Example:
  --------
  > Imagine a new switch just out of the box, it can connect cables and has an IP
    address, but nothing else is set up.

 What happens after Greenfield Import:
  > Many advanced features are enabled and configured.
    BGP (for routing between networks)
    OSPF (for internal routing)
    VXLAN/EVPN (for network virtualization))
    PIM (multicast routing)
    LCAP (link aggregation)
    LLDP (device discovery)) etc..

  - Loopback interfaces are created for routing and VXLAN endpoints
  - NVE (Network Virtualization Edge) interfaces are set up for VXLAN
  - All Ethernet ports are set to high MTU (9216 bytes), trunk mode, and edge truck
    for spanning-tree
  - Anycast gateway MAC is set (helps with seamless host movement)
  - Hardware QoS and other fabric settings are added
  - DHCP relay and SNMP monitoring are enabled
  - Overlay (virtual network) and underlay (physical network) are separated
    and configured.))

Example:
========
Now the switch is like a fully set up office network:
 - it can talk to other offices (BGP/OSPF),
 - it can create virtual networks for different teams (VXLAN/EVPN),
 - it can handle big data packets (MTU 9216)
 - it can monitor and manage traffic (Qos, SNMP)


Why is this important:
======================
 Before: The switch is just a basic device with minimal functionality,
         not ready for modern data center needs.

 After: The switch is fully ready for a scalable, flexible and virtualized
        data center network.

 In simple words:
 ================
  Greenfield Import:
  like installing all the apps and settings those you need
  on a new smartphone, so it's ready to use for everything you want.

  Before: Just a phone, no apps

  After: All apps, settings, and accounts are set up for your job

Topology_connections:
=====================
        [Border-1]                # Border: Connects to external network (WAN/Internet)
           /     \
   [Spine-1]   [Spine-2]          # Spine: Fabric core, connects all leaves
      |           |
[Leaf-Agg-1] [Leaf-Agg-2]         # Aggregation Leaf: Aggregates ToR/Leafs, vPC for redundancy
      |           |
    [Leaf-1]                     # Edge/Compute Leaf: Connects to compute nodes/endpoints
      |
   [TOR-1]---[TOR-2]              # ToR: Top of Rack switches, connect directly to servers/endpoints


Comments for each device role:
==============================
Border-1: Entry/exit point for the data center, connectes to outside the world.
Spine-1/2: Core of the fabric, high-speed interconnect for all leaves.
Leaf-Agg-1/2: Aggregation layer, provides redundancy and uplinks aggregation for edge leaves.
Leaf-1: Edge/Compute leaf, connects to application servers and endpoints or compute nodee (VMs/containers)
TOR-1/2: Top of Rack switches, connects directly to servers in the rack, often paired for redundancy.

Key Points:
===========
All traffic between racks or leaves goes thorugh the spine layer.
Redundant paths at each laery for high availability.
vPC (virtual port channel)) pairs at aggregation and ToR layers for load balancing and failover.













